# Car Telemetry System — Kafka Implementation

## Overview
Evolution of the gRPC implementation replacing synchronous gRPC transport
with asynchronous Kafka messaging. Same functionality, better scalability
and decoupling.

## Architecture
[Car Producer] → Kafka Topic → [Car Consumer] → MongoDB
(car-positions)      ↓
[Analytics Service]
↓
[REST API :8080]

## Tech Stack
- **Java 21** + **Spring Boot 3.2.5**
- **Kafka** — asynchronous transport (KRaft mode, no Zookeeper)
- **Protobuf** — message serialization
- **MongoDB** — storage for positions, trips and alerts
- **Docker** — containerized deployment

## Key Differences from gRPC Branch
| | gRPC | Kafka |
|---|---|---|
| Communication | Synchronous | Asynchronous |
| Coupling | Tight | Loose |
| Producer needs consumer running | Yes | No |
| Message replay | No | Yes |
| Scalability | Limited | High |
| Fault tolerance | Low | High |

## Running the System
```bash
# start all services
docker-compose up --build

# verify data flowing
curl http://localhost:8080/vehicles | jq
curl http://localhost:8080/analytics/summary | jq
```

## Kafka Topic
- **Topic:** `car-positions`
- **Key:** VIN (ensures ordering per vehicle)
- **Value:** Protobuf serialized `CarPosition`
- **Partitioning:** by VIN key

## REST API
| Endpoint | Description |
|---|---|
| `GET /vehicles` | List all vehicle VINs |
| `GET /vehicles/{vin}/trip/current` | Active trip |
| `GET /vehicles/{vin}/trips` | Completed trips |
| `GET /vehicles/{vin}/alerts` | Speed alerts |
| `GET /vehicles/{vin}/positions` | Recent positions |
| `GET /analytics/summary` | Fleet summary |
| `GET /analytics/{vin}/summary` | Vehicle summary |
| `POST /analytics/process` | Trigger analytics |

## Why Kafka over gRPC?
- Producer and consumer are fully decoupled
- Producer doesn't need consumer to be running
- Messages are persisted in Kafka — replay on consumer restart
- Naturally scales to multiple producers and consumers
- Foundation for Flink stream processing (see `flink` branch)

## Limitations
- Scheduled batch analytics — not truly real-time
- Analytics runs every 10 minutes or on-demand via REST
- See `flink` branch for real-time stream processing solution

## Next Steps
See `flink` branch for Apache Flink implementation replacing
scheduled analytics with real-time stream processing.